# Links Beta

> Capture it. Connect it. Actually use it.

Links Beta is a local-first AI research workspace for people who deal with messy information, half-finished ideas, evidence trails, scattered notes, and too many tabs.

It is built to help you collect material, organise it into isolated project spaces, and turn raw inputs into something usable: searchable context, linked evidence, summaries, questions, patterns, and deeper research workflows.

This is not pretending to be magic.
It is a serious beta with a lot already working, a lot being refined, and a lot more still coming.

---

## What Links Beta is

Links is a private, modular research and intelligence system built around the idea that your data should stay under your control.

You can capture text, links, documents, images, audio, notes, and research threads into separate project spaces called **pots**. From there, Links can process that material in the background and help you explore what matters:
- what something is about
- who or what is mentioned
- what connects to what
- what looks important
- what is missing
- what deserves a deeper look

It is designed for people who want more than a chatbot and less than a bloated corporate surveillance platform.

---

## Who this is for

Links Beta is especially relevant for:

### Researchers
Academic, technical, scientific, OSINT, private or independent research where source handling and context matter.

### Investigators and analysts
Anyone trying to connect people, events, claims, documents, timelines, contradictions, or patterns without losing the trail.

### Legal and case-prep workflows
Teams or individuals organising evidence, transcripts, notes, references, and related documents in isolated workspaces.

### Founders, builders and developers
People exploring ideas, saving technical material, researching products, planning projects, comparing tools, or mapping opportunities.

### Serious knowledge workers
If your current workflow is “50 tabs, 7 notes apps, a pile of PDFs, and vibes”, this exists for you.

---

## What it does

## 1. Capture into isolated project spaces
Store research inside separate **pots** so projects do not bleed into each other.

Capture can include:
- text snippets
- saved links
- PDFs and documents
- images and screenshots
- audio and transcripts
- notes and chat context

## 2. Process material in the background
Once content is in, Links can process it in the background and turn it into structured, usable layers such as:
- tags
- summaries
- extracted entities
- linked relationships
- searchable context
- research artifacts

## 3. Keep originals separate from AI output
Original captures stay original.
AI-generated outputs are treated as derived layers, not rewritten truth.

That matters a lot when you are working with evidence, nuance, or anything that should not be silently “improved” into nonsense.

## 4. Let you explore with AI chat
Each project space can become a working context for chat, questioning, summarising, comparing, and analysis.

Instead of throwing random prompts into the void and hoping for the best, the system is built to work with the material you actually saved.

## 5. Run deeper research workflows
Links is also aimed at more advanced research flows:
- structured question generation
- deeper report building
- cross-source analysis
- contradiction spotting
- follow-up paths and open loops
- project planning and intelligence generation

## 6. Stay local-first and privacy-conscious
The philosophy is simple:
your research should not become somebody else’s training data, product telemetry, or quiet little goldmine.

---

## Why it is different

A lot of AI tools want to be your everything while quietly owning your data, your workflow, and your future migration pain.

Links goes in a different direction:

- local-first by design
- privacy-respecting
- modular instead of locked down
- built around provenance and auditability
- focused on real research and real workflows
- flexible model choice rather than one-provider dependency
- designed to grow into a serious personal or professional intelligence environment

In plain English: less hype castle, more useful machine.

---

## Current beta status

Links Beta is already well beyond a napkin concept.

A large part of the core system is working and usable, including the foundations for:
- structured capture
- encrypted/local asset handling
- background processing
- search and organisation
- AI-assisted tagging and summarisation
- link discovery between related material
- chat and research workflows
- exportable project-style data handling
- extension and desktop-oriented thinking

That said, this is still a beta.
Some areas are polished.
Some are rough.
Some are experimental.
Some are still being actively designed before they get wired in properly.

I am not pitching perfection.
I am pitching a real system with real momentum.

---

## Example use cases

### Investigative work
Build a project pot around a topic, person, case, or event.
Save articles, docs, images, notes, transcripts, and links.
Let the system help surface entities, overlaps, contradictions, and connection paths.

### Technical research
Collect documentation, code references, diagrams, papers, issue threads, and implementation notes in one place.
Use chat and deep analysis to reduce context switching and keep the whole thing searchable.

### Product and startup research
Track competitors, ideas, customer problems, feature references, market signals, and technical options without creating a chaotic graveyard of bookmarks.

### Personal knowledge system
Use it as a serious second-brain-style environment for things you actually care about, while keeping control over what is stored, what is processed, and what is remembered.

---

## Planned directions

Links is being shaped as a broader ecosystem, not just a single narrow tool.

Areas being explored or actively designed include:
- voice mode
- richer browser workflows
- RSS intelligence and feed discovery
- calendar and timeline linking
- DYK-style surfaced insights
- wellness and nutrition style modules
- mixture-of-models orchestration
- self-evolving agent workflows
- advertising / outreach support modules
- more autonomous but still controlled research flows

The goal is not to bolt on random gimmicks.
The goal is to build a modular system where useful capabilities can plug into the same core architecture without turning the product into spaghetti with branding.

---

## Open source / repo intent

This repository exists as the public-facing base for Links Beta.

Depending on timing and direction, it may include:
- documentation
- concept and architecture material
- selected code
- test builds
- beta binaries
- integration examples
- public discussion around the direction of the project

So yes, this is part product page, part technical signal, part “here’s the machine I’ve been building”.

---

## Why I am sharing it

Because there is a real gap between:
- generic AI chat tools
- enterprise sludge
- and the kind of system power users actually want for private, serious, evolving work

Links is my attempt to build something better in that gap.

